/* =====================================================================
   DATA — this is the part you own. Edit this file only; index.html
   never needs to change when you add, remove, or fix a resource.

   How to add a row:
     1. Get lat/lng by right-clicking any spot in Google Maps.
     2. region:   1=Northeast  2=Southeast  3=Midwest  4=Southwest  5=West
        (state → region mapping lives in scripts/make-regions.js)
        st: two-letter state/territory code — drives the state drill-down.
     3. category: con | meetup | ctf | maker | school | library | youth | gov
        | hamradio
     4. url / address / phone / when / org may be "" or omitted if
        unknown — the popup simply omits empty fields. Never guess
        contact details. org = who runs it, only when verifiable;
        sponsors rotate yearly, so they belong on the linked site,
        not in this file.
     5. next: "YYYY-MM-DD" — machine-readable start date for dated events.
        Powers the Upcoming panel and expired-date flagging; omit for
        recurring meetups and undated entries.
     6. topics: ["ai","cloud",...] — OPTIONAL, cross-cutting interest tags,
        independent of category. Only add when a resource's actual focus
        is clear from its name/notes/org — not every row needs one. Fixed
        taxonomy (kept in sync with TOPICS in index.html): ai, cloud,
        osint, iot, radio (SDR/RF — deliberately overlaps the hamradio
        category), crypto (cryptography/PQC), redteam, blueteam, forensics,
        malware, physical (lockpicking/physical security),
        socialengineering, supplychain, privacy, policy, ics (SCADA/
        industrial/OT), ctf (a con/meetup that *hosts* a CTF, distinct
        from the ctf category), community (youth/diversity-focused).
        crypto and supplychain were coined 2026-07-19 directly from real
        con track/talk names (not guessed in advance) — when a future pass
        finds another recurring, distinct theme in real talk data, add it
        the same way rather than forcing it into an existing tag. See
        STATES.md "Topic tags + con talks" section for the full
        methodology.
     7. talks: [{ title, speaker, track, topics:[...] }] — OPTIONAL,
        con-category only. Individual sessions/villages worth surfacing
        under a topic search. Only populate from an actually-published
        schedule — never fabricate a lineup for an unannounced con. This
        is the field the monthly refresh script should extend over time;
        see STATES.md for which cons have it today and why.
     8. events: [{ title, when, topics:[...] }] — OPTIONAL, any category
        except con (which uses talks instead). Real recurring or dated
        programming at a space — a class, workshop, open hack night,
        teen tech program, themed meetup topic — pulled from that
        resource's own published calendar/events page. Same rule as
        talks: only from an actually-published listing, never invented.
        `when` is free text (e.g. "Every Tuesday, 6pm" or "Sep 12") since
        most library/makerspace calendars don't give machine-parseable
        single dates the way con `next` does.

   Data sweep: July 2026. This is a national map, so it carries the
   anchors — the cons, groups, spaces, schools, and hubs people actually
   use to plug into the community. Venues and schedules drift; the notes
   flag anything to re-verify. Florida has its own deep-dive map
   (florida-cyber-map) — only its statewide anchors are repeated here.
   ===================================================================== */
